The '''Huntington's Disease Association''' (HDA) is a charity that supports people in England and Wales affected by the [[Heredity|genetic]] [[neurodegeneration|neurodegenerative]] brain condition [[Huntington's disease]] (HD).

The HDA was founded in 1986 and is based in [[Liverpool]].<ref name=companieshouse>{{cite web|title=Huntington's Disease Association|url=http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk/a23479d1ae2ae627b38953307f81bb88/compdetails|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=10 December 2011}}</ref> It supports a network of regional care advisors who offer care and support to people with and at risk of Huntington's disease and their families. The HDA also has a research programme that supports scientific and social research into HD.<ref name=abouthda>{{cite web|title=Regional Care Advisors|url=http://www.hda.org.uk/hda/care-advisers.html|publisher=HDA|accessdate=10 December 2011}}</ref> It has worked to establish and support a network of [[multidisciplinary]] clinics for HD patients in the UK.<ref name=charityaward />

The charity was instrumental in the 2010 launch of an [[All-Party Parliamentary Group]] for Huntington’s disease in the [[UK Parliament]], chaired by [[Lord Walton of Detchant]], and 2010 research revealing that the [[prevalence]] of HD is much higher than previously thought.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rawlins|first=M|title=Huntington's disease out of the closet?|journal=Lancet|date=2010 Oct 23|volume=376|issue=9750|pages=1372–3|pmid=20594589|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(10)60974-9}}</ref><ref name=indep>{{cite news|last=Silverman|first=Rosa|title=Huntington's Disease cases 'under-estimated'|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/huntingtons-disease-cases-underestimated-2014389.html|accessdate=10 December 2011|newspaper=Independent|date=2010-06-30}}</ref>

The HDA won the 2005 [[UK Charity Awards|UK Charity Award]] for healthcare and medical research<ref name=charityaward>{{cite web|title=2005 winners|url=http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/charityawards/winners/2005/winners/healthcare_and_medical_research/content/9371/huntingtons_disease_association|publisher=Charity Awards|accessdate=10 December 2011}}</ref> and the 2005 [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] (NHS) Health and Social Care Award for long term conditions.<ref name=nhsaward2005>{{cite web|title=2005 Health and Social Care Awards|url=http://www.institute.nhs.uk/HSCA/national/_content/health_and_social_care_-_past_winners/national_winners_and_finalists_2005.aspx|publisher=NHS|accessdate=10 December 2011}}</ref>

The HDA's patrons are [[Patricia Lascelles, Countess of Harewood|Patricia, Countess of Harewood]], singer [[Tony Hadley]] and entertainer [[Shane Richie]].<ref name=patrons>{{cite news|last=Lomas|first=Clare|title=Tony Hadley and Shane Richie named Huntington’s Disease Association’s new patrons|url=http://www.nursingtimes.net/whats-new-in-nursing/primary-care/tony-hadley-and-shane-richie-named-huntingtons-disease-associations-new-patrons/5002692.article|accessdate=10 December 2011|newspaper=Nursing Times|date=2009-06-11}}</ref> 

The HDA is part of the UK HD Alliance, along with the Scottish Huntington's Association and HD Association Northern Ireland.<ref name=patrons /> It is also a member of the International Huntington Alliance.<ref name=iha>{{cite web|title=List of member organisations|url=http://www.huntington-assoc.com/ihaadr.htm|publisher=IHA|accessdate=10 December 2011}}</ref>

